Page Content:
0b885b7f-2b42-41b1-8a5e-f0dc5e91cb27:Growth_purple:#EAE6FFüå±Welcome to Confluence!You can use Confluence to create a rich knowledge base or to collaborate with others using words, videos, images, graphics, charts, and graphs.This page walks you through some Confluence basics like spaces, pages, and elements that allow you to create and manage impactful content for your teams.On this pageOn-this-page11trueflatConfluence 101https://www.youtube.com/embed/kaNPNbAT-as%22üóÉÔ∏è SpacesSpaces are places for individuals, teams, and companies to organize and work on ideas, projects, documentation, and announcements. Spaces can be customized and integrated with both Atlassian tools and others. Create as many spaces as you need to get things done:
Blueteam spacesGive each team their own space so they can work closely and make information easier to find.
Yellowproject spacesPut all the information related to your project in one place so everyone can work together.
Greenpersonal spacesStore anything you‚Äôre working on, keep your to-do lists, and polish content before moving it into a shared space.
16
incomplete
In the main navigation bar, select Spaces‚Üí Create space to create a new space.
More about spaces
üìÑ ContentWhiteboards are your team‚Äôs place to brainstorm, build connections, and make ideas come to life.Pages are the building blocks of Confluence. Drop ideas into a page, to collaborate on, refine, and document work.Blog posts are individually-authored pieces of content that illustrate a particular perspective, typically shared broadly‚Äîgreat for documenting case studies or broad insights.
To create a content within a space, select the + and choose your content type. You can also create content using the Create button in the main navigation bar.
17
incomplete
Press c to create content at any time.
More about pages | More about whiteboardsVisualize the relationship between spaces and pagesBack to top ‚§¥Making purposeful content
‚úèÔ∏è Confluence editorChanges can only be made to page content when in the editor. Changes will save automatically and be pushed live the next time the page is published.üõ†Ô∏è TemplatesIf you‚Äôre not sure where to start when setting up a new space or content, save time with a template.
35
incomplete
Press e when on a page to open the editor.
More about page templates | Browse space templates
üß∞ ElementsElements are tools like calendars, note panels, and layouts, designed to help you make your pages more powerful.
20
incomplete
Press/to see a list of elements.
More about elements
üì∏ Header imagesMake your pages more visually impactful with emojis and header images. üçï Emojis aren‚Äôt just a fun way to spice up your page‚Äîthey also show up in search, so using them strategically makes it easier to find pages later on.
21
incomplete
Select Add status at the top of the page, so teammates can see your progress at a glance.
More about page header imagesBack to top ‚§¥Collaborating with teammatesüßë‚Äçüíª Real-time editingYou and up to 11 teammates can edit a page together in real time. Changes save and sync automatically so that everyone editing sees the same thing. Start editing together by selecting the Edit icon in the header.
22
incomplete
Press Command + Enter when in the editor to publish.
More about collaborative editingüí¨ Mentions and commentsComments are a great way to start a conversation about a page or blog post. They allow you to remark on content, add important information, ask questions, and generally drive collaboration and teamwork.@mention a teammate to bring them into the conversation, and they can reply to and/or like comments.Leave comments for your team in different places, depending on the type of feedback you have:
23
incomplete
Inline comment ‚ÜíAdded to a highlighted section of the page or post you are editing or viewing; good for targeted comments on a specific word or phrase.
24
incomplete
Page comment ‚ÜíAdded below the content of the page or post you are viewing; good for comments that apply to the content as a whole.
25
incomplete
Leave an inline comment when viewing a page or in the editor.
More about commentsBack to top ‚§¥Organizing your content
üå≥ Content treeThe content tree is where your content is organized within a space. Drag and drop to reorder or nest content, so you can more effectively share your work with others.
1970
incomplete
After you publish, select [ to expand or collapse the content tree.
More about the content tree
üì£ Space overviewTo help your teammates find relevant content, curate your space overview with useful elements like calendars and page statuses, and include information about what is in your space.
26
incomplete
Use the /info panel element to highlight important information in your space overview.
More about space overviewüåª Content types
WHITEBOARDIf your content still isn‚Äôt defined, whiteboards are a quick way to get messy ideas from many collaborators documented.
BLOG POSTIf your content that won‚Äôt change over time, create it as a blog post. The blog feed for each space displays the most recent posts first.
PAGEIf your content may change over time, create it as a page. Pages nest, so you can create categories and subcategories.
27
incomplete
Press k for a shareable link to your page or post.
More about sharing content | More about whiteboards
üìè TablesTables allow you to organize important information on a page to discuss it with your team. Present the information the way it makes sense to you‚Äîresize columns, color cells, rows and columns, and sort the table by clicking the column headers.
28
incomplete
Type /table to add a table at any time.
More about tables
üå± DraftsConfluence autosaves your content as you work‚Äîif you select Close in the editor without publishing, you‚Äôll create a draft, or an unpublished page you can get back to at any time.
draftOnly you can see your draft, unless you share a link to it.More about draftsBack to top ‚§¥What‚Äôs next?üßê TL;DR
These are the top three actions we think will help you get the most from Confluence.
